  "$comment": "Hand-authored cross-language parity corpus for postal-code validation — the SOURCE OF TRUTH for expected behavior. Both runtimes (.NET DcsvIo.D2.Validation.DefaultPostalCodeValidator and TS @dcsv-io/d2-validation DefaultPostalCodeValidator) compile the SAME per-country regex map from the single shared dataset contracts/validation/postal-code-regexes.json, then READ this corpus and ASSERT each row; neither runtime emits either file. The shared dataset is ported from postcode-validator 3.10.9 with one deliberate correction ('[A-z]' -> '[A-Za-z]' in the UK/GB patterns, an upstream bug); the 'invalid-gb-caret-in-letter-position' row pins that fix (a caret in a letter position — accepted by the buggy '[A-z]', rejected by the corrected '[A-Za-z]'). All codes are synthetic / well-known — no real PII. Both validators normalize (trim + uppercase) before matching; an unknown OR absent country FAILS CLOSED (ValidationFailed, never a permissive fallback) on both runtimes. 'valid' rows carry the expected 'normalized' (trim + uppercase) form and a 'country' (ISO alpha-2); '!valid' rows carry 'errorKey'. Inputs are either a literal 'input' string or synthesized from 'inputKind' (null | whitespace | oversized) with optional 'char' + 'inputRepeat' (oversized => char.repeat(inputRepeat)). Both runtimes synthesize identically.",
